 The client-server architecture is minimal and largely decoupled:

  Server Side (Flask):
  - snake_game/server/web_server.py:8 — SnakeGameServer serves static files and one route:
    - GET / → renders index.html with color config
    - GET /api/colors → returns the JSON color palette
  - No game state, no WebSocket, no persistent sessions. Server is purely a static file + template host.

  Client Side (Browser):
  - All game logic lives in snake_game/static/js/game.js (~795 lines).
  - Game state (snake, food, score, powerUps, etc.) is held entirely in-memory in the SnakeGame class.
  - localStorage is used only for persisting highScore across page reloads.
  - The game loop (setInterval) runs 100% client-side. No network calls during gameplay.

  Communication:
  - Server sends initial color theme on page load via template variable.
  - Zero runtime API calls. The /api/colors endpoint is defined but never called from the client.

  Implications:
  - Game state is not shareable or recoverable.
  - No cheating possible via server manipulation because the server knows nothing.
  - Refreshing the page loses all progress except the high score.

  In short: the server is a thin delivery vehicle; the browser owns the entire simulation.
